bug.short_desc: StackOverflowError when searching for a methods references

long_desc.thetext:
When searching for References in the workspace, a StackOverflow occurs.
What steps will reproduce the problem? 1. Open a .class file with added sources (it has the J010-Icon and shows source code) 2. Select a method: click on "getProperty" (it will be highlighted)

3. Press Shift-Ctrl-G or select from menu: Search->References->Workspace
A window pops up, reporting a StackOverflowError.

The current bug is a bug in JDT indeed, so the fix will probably go into Kepler M6 (Juno SR2 is closed).
As to patching JDT/Core: - JDT is under the EPL, so everybody may take the sources and modify. - Technically, this implies that a "patch feature" is shipped, which tells the OSGi framework to replace the existing bundle with another version. - Patch features have limitations wrt shared installs, e.g., it's not possible that a user installs a patch feature that replaces a bundle in the shared install (cf. bug 281510) - In the end its the user's choice whether s/he agrees to installing a modified version of - say - org.eclipse.jdt.core - Users should be actively informed when they are about to replace an existing bundle with a variant, for a dual purpose actually: - so they can decide whether patching is OK for them - so that bug reports go to the proper team (JDT wouldn't want to chase bugs introduced by the Groovy plug-in). I've suggested to add more information to the install dialogs; visibility of patch features and explanation of their effects could IMHO still be improved, but nobody really seemed to want this (cf. bug 316702).
I happen to share the same background as Groovy, since in my other project, Object Teams, we use the same strategy, replacing org.eclipse.jdt.core with an adapted variant. Object Teams got the official OK from the corresponding committees and was approved for the simultaneous release train. Groovy chose a different channel for distribution, so approval by Eclipse committees is not an issue for them.
As for the exact update strategy, you'd have to ask the Andies, at what frequency they merge upstream changes and how long it will take until a change shows up in their release. From Object Teams I know that it is possible to provide same-day updates, i.e., on each release of the Eclipse simultaneous release, the Object Teams variant contains all fixes of the corresponding JDT/Core version. Except for the different release schedules I see no reason, why this would be different for Groovy, but that's their business :)

Stephan, thanks for the good explanation. The Groovy-Eclipse project tends to only release patches of JDT for GA, SR1, SR2, and probably a milestone or two before the GA. The reason is that creating the patch is a manual process (it sounds like OT has automated the patching process). Our changes are not significant (typically, the changes are just hooks in JDT to call our code), but we prefer the manual process so that we can be sure that everything merges properly. We also try extremely hard to ensure that if your project is not a Groovy project, then there is 0 impact from our patch.
That being said, we could of course do more to ensure that people installing Groovy-Eclipse and our JDT patch know what they are getting into. We already include this information in our feature descriptions, but I'm not sure how many people actually read that.
As I said. we don't typically recreate the JDT patch for projects outside of the standard JDT release cycle, but if this fix is small (which it sounds like it is), we can certainly pick up the patch.

Hello, The problem (i.e the infinite recursion) is occurring due to the inability to verify the location (i.e the token number in a compound name), while doing the name comparison. That is why, if two different segments in a compound name are same, while comparing, they are not differentiated (only string comparison is done). getTypeOrPackage only takes the name fragment (one segment of the compound name). Hence it does not have enough information to do location based comparison. (getType, at least takes the full compound name, and has the information.) As a solution, planning to pass the location info into getTypeOrPackage, so that, when the name comparison succeeds, the location equality will also be verified before approving that as equal [in the line Scope.java :: getTypeOrpackage :: if (CharOperation.equals(importBinding.compoundName[importBinding.compoundName.length - 1], name)) ] Please let me know if anyone has any comment. Thanks Anirban

Conflict detection for (static) imports has been considerably overhauled via bug 361327 indeed.

Some more facts collected to increase confidence in the proposed solution:
bug 361327 introduced a new method CompilationUnitScope#checkMoreStaticBindings(). For test084 this method detects a conflict between an imported method and type both of name p1.Bar.B. Via checkAndRecordImportBinding an ImportConflictBinding is created (which before bug 361327 was not created), added to tempImports and finally to typeOrPackageCache. When a SingleTypeReference (with name "B") triggers Scope.getType("B") the ImportConflictBinding is found in the typeOrPackageCache. Inside getTypeOrPackage we extract the conflictingTypeBinding and resolution succeeds well before the critical code section. This flow looks pretty solid to me.
Summary: Before bug 318401 the deadly recursion was not possible. Since bug 361327 more analysis is done up-front, rendering the fix for bug 318401 obsolete.
